<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="2399d79c-bb86-57de-9af1-059c6080f7e0" activityNameId="d1c195bb-8042-4b37-a024-87e473cb5f04" parentActivityId="0951ee99-0dde-44ad-8343-287aea61d197" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">methylene diphenyl diisocyanate production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Bis(4-isocyanatophenyl)methane</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">4,4'-Diphenylmethane diisocyanate</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Methylbisphenyl isocyanate</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Diphenylmethane diisocyanate</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">4,4'-Methylenebis(phenyl isocyanate)</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends once  the products, i.e., 1 kg of methylene diphenyl diisocyanate and 0.52 kg of hydrochloric acid, are at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.

</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the average production of 1 kg of methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI). At the same time, the formed hydrochloric acid is treated as a valuable by-product. Even though MDI exists in three isomers, 4.4-MDI is the most widely used in industrial applications and is the one represented in this dataset. This dataset was extrapolated from the European dataset (ISOPA, 2021), and thus the European average production technology was applied. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">MDI (CAS: 101-68-8) is an aromatic diisocyanate that is used in the production of polyurethane foams in combination with polyols (Boustead 2005). Polyurethane foams show good thermal insulation properties, and thus, are used extensively in the manufacture of freezers and refrigerators, and in building and automotive applications. In 2012 the largest producer of MDI globally was Bayer, producing 1.24 million tonnes per year, followed by Wanhua Group, producing 1.1 million tonnes per year (Gal, 2012).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The industrial preparation of isocyanates is carried out with the reaction of an amine with phosgene in an aromatic solvent. In more detail, the production scheme for MDI can be breakdown into the following chemical reactions:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Methylene dianiline (MDA) production from aniline and formaldehyde: 2C6H7N + CH2O -&gt; C13H14N2+H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">MDA phosgenation: C13H14N2  + 2COCl2  -&gt; C15H10N2O2  + 4HCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">This dataset is based on industry data from five different MDI producers with six plants in five European countries participated in the primary data collection.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Christian Six, Frank Richter (2011): Isocyanates, organic, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Heino Falcke, Simon Holbrook, Iain Clenahan,Alfredo Lopez Carretero, Teoman Sanalan,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Thomas Brinkmann, Joze Roth, Benoit Zerger</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10"> Serge Roudier, Luis Delgado Sancho (2017): Best Available Techniques (BAT) Reference Document for the Production of large Volume Organic Chemicals</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of toluene diisocyanate (TDI) and methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI) , 3 - SeparatePublication</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">G. Margaret Wells, “Handbook of Petrochemicals and Processes”, 2nd edition, Ashgate, 1999</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13">Boustead. 2005. Eco-profiles of the European Plastics Industry Diphenylmethane diisocyanate (MDI). Retrieved from: http://www.polyurethanes.org/uploads/documents/eco_midi.pdf, accessed 26 January 2017</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="14">Gal, J. 2012. Wanhua to the rescue of BorsodChem. ICIS Chemical Business. Retrieved from: http://www.icis.com/resources/news/2012/02/20/9533156/wanhua-to-the-rescue-of-borsodchem/, accessed 26 Janury 2017</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="15">[This dataset is meant to replace the following datasets:]</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="4a11cbd4-74bf-47fb-9fe5-6e97e3db136b">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2013:Manufacture of plastics and synthetic rubber in primary forms</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset was extrapolated from the European dataset (ISOPA, 2021). Therefore, the European average production technology was applied. Representative 100% of European (EU-28) production of methylene diphenyl diisocyanate.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This inventory represents the average production of methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI), provided as a generic dataset, starting with aniline and formaldehyde as raw materials.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">In more detail, the chemical processes involved in the MDI production are described below.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">First, methylene dianiline (MDA) is produced through the reaction of formaldehyde with aniline, in the presence of  hydrochloric acid catalyst. As MDI exists in three isomers, a distribution of MDI isomers is obtained, where their share depends on the ratio of aniline to formaldehyde, the acid concentration, and the reaction conditions.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Methylene dianiline (MDA) synthesis: 2C6H7N + CH2O -&gt; C13H14N2+H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">The mixture at the reactor outlet is neutralised with caustic soda, and separated into an organic phase and an inorganic (aqueous) phase. The latter phase contains the crude MDA isomer mixture, and is washed. Excess amounts of aniline are recovered with distillation and recycled to the MDA synthesis stage. At the same time, the inorganic (aqueous) phase is further purified from any residual organic substance, and subsequently discharged for additional treatment and recovery stages.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">The crude MDA isomer mixture is subsequently treated with phosgene to produce an MDI isomer mixture in solution, along with HCl byproduct.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">MDA phosgenation: C13H14N2  + 2COCl2  -&gt; C15H10N2O2  + 4HCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">In absence of phosgene in the form of a raw material, this intermediate is produced on-side from carbon monoxide and chlorine.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Phosgene production: CO + Cl2 --&gt;  COCl2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">The crude MDI solution is first separated by the solvent, which is recovered via distillation, and subsequently purified through fractional distillation, crystallisation, or sublimation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of toluene diisocyanate (TDI) and methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI) , 3 - SeparatePublication</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2020-01-01" endDate="2026-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Data collection for production was collected as 12-month averages representing the year 2018. The inventory creation and calculation stage was concluded in 2020, while the technology is not expected to change until 2026.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
